<HEAD>Fire Near Aquatic Park Destroys Eight Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIMAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire Monday near an aquatic park that boasts `` five million gallons'' burned about 10 acres of brush before it was extinguished, and destroyed eight cars, authorities said. Firefighters had some difficulty in controlling the fire at first because `` there's no fire hydrant in the parking lot. We ca n't get any water to the cars,'' <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> fire Inspector <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenihan </PERSON> said. County fire Capt. <PERSON> Garry </PERSON> <PERSON> Oversby </PERSON> said later that water was rerouted from hydrants nearby. It was not immediately known whether the blaze began in a vehicle or on the vegetation in <LOCATION> Bonnelli </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, but the flames leaped from car to car, <PERSON> Oversby </PERSON> said. The fire was reported shortly after 2 p.m. in an overflow parking area for Raging Waters amusement park less than one mile away. The park was not evacuated and no one was injured. `` Raging Waters is 44 acres, five million gallons and tons of fun for everyone,'' said a tape-recorded message at the park, about 25 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The park features 12 water slides, a fresh-water surf pool, and a river-rafting ride. Damage was estimated at $ 50,000, Oversby said.
