<HEAD>Official says China is not a major arms dealer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s top military official, speaking to reporters Tuesday before meeting with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Defense Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is not a major arms dealer. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is a developing country. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> can only sell a little. It is only a small fraction of what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has sold,'' Defense Minister <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiwei </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s sales of missiles to <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> nations, including Silkworm missiles to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, have been criticized by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. According to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> figures, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> sold about $ 2 billion worth of arms last year, mainly to developing countries. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> does not provide information on its arms sales. <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and other Third World countries sell only conventional arms `` but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is selling advanced arms such as the F-16'' jet fighter. `` We ca n't compare the two kinds of arms,'' he said. Deputy Chief of Staff <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> <PERSON> Xin </PERSON>, also talking to reporters in the Great Hall of the People, insisted <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> strictly regulates its arms sales. `` First, they are for defense. Second, they are for maintaining stability and peace, not war,'' he said. Earlier Tuesday the American national anthem echoed off the gray walls of the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> as <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s top military leaders welcomed <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> on his first official visit. <PERSON> Carlu