<HEAD>Dozens Arrested Trying To Distribute Free Food</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after fourth `It was...' with advocacy group
giving city an ``award.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifty people were arrested Monday when a group trying to distribute free food and leaflets scuffled with police, who had previously warned the group to get a permit or move elsewhere. A television cameraman was injured when a police officer knocked him to the ground at the fracas on the edge of Golden Gate Park. Food and fists went flying when a squad of police officers wearing riot gear closed in on about 200 people gathered for the `` Food Not Bombs'' give-away. It was the second time in a week the group had clashed with police. On Aug. 29, 29 people were arrested in a similar confrontation. Group leaders said they will return each Monday. Later Monday in <LOCATION> Warwick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, a group active on behalf of the homeless, the <ORGANIZATION> Gandhi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, gave its annual <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoinette </PERSON> Award for Community Consciousness to the city of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> to recognize the arrests. The tongue-in-cheek award refers to the French queen's famous remark of, `` Let them eat cake,'' when told the peasants were without bread. The latest confrontation took place about 45 minutes after the group marched into the southeast corner of the park, adjacent to the <LOCATION> Haight-Ashbury </LOCATION> district, popular in the 1960s among hippies and in the'80s among people who buy and restore Victorian homes. Police moved in as the group's members began giving food to one another. Police spokesman Sgt. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Senkir </PERSON> said it was considered an illegal give-away after food was given to 25 people. As the officers approached, food began to fly through the air. One officer was hit in the face with a plate of rice and another was struck in the neck with a tomato. A police officer grabbed <ORGANIZATION> KPIX </ORGANIZATION> cameraman <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoepp </PERSON>, knocking him to the ground. The cameraman lay stunned for a few moments with blood trickling from his cheek and his camera tossed aside. He then got up and resumed filming the clash. Some of those arrested were dragged away with their wrists bound by plastic ties. They were loaded into police vans and taken away. <PERSON> Senkir </PERSON> said they faced a possible misdemeanor count of creating a nuisance and two park infractions: illegal distribution of food and illegal leafleting. The park infractions carry a maximum penalty of a $ 50 fine. <PERSON> Senkir </PERSON> said one woman also faced a charge of assaulting an officer. <PERSON> Senkir </PERSON> said the giveaway would not be illegal if the group had obtained permits. He said the group had been offered other sites for the give-away, but rejected that idea. The group had 15 to 20 cartons of food, including bread, carrots, lettuce, rice, melons and corn. The leaflets said the group had been harassed in recent months by police and had been unfairly characterized by Mayor <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnos </PERSON> as being interested in exploiting the homeless and hungry. <PERSON> Patrisha </PERSON> <PERSON> Vestey </PERSON>, who was handing out deviled eggs, said she was a legal assistant in a law office and lived in the neighborhood. `` I disapproved of what the police are doing. I think the poor should be taken care of,'' she said. It was not clear if she was a member of the group. <PERSON> Lorraine </PERSON> <PERSON> Rorke </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Stanyan-Fulton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I'm against this particular give-away in this particular location. `` I also feel that they are not so interested in giving away food as they are in promoting their particular message,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Rorke </PERSON>, whose organization is one of several neighborhood associations opposed to the `` Food Not Bombs'' give-aways. `` It's a free country, and if they want to have their political views, they can have them. I just do n't like their means of using the hungry and blocking the entrance to the park,'' she said.
