<HEAD>U.S. Forces In South Korea Help To Safeguard Olympics</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> are helping to protect the Olympic Games. The writer, the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>' bureau chief in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, went on a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> flight to get a view of the preparations
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOVE NIGHTMARE RANGE, South Kore (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Capt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON> scanned the target and flung the plane in a stomach-wrenching attack dive into the rocky valley below. The small <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> OV-10 Bronco nose-dived, the force of the acceleration forcing its two occupants back against their armor-plated seats. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> flashed past as <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON> streaked toward the target, calmly checking the attack coordinates. White phosphorous rockets flashed from the plane's belly and slammed into the practice target as the pilot jerked the plane up over a rock cliff. <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON> glanced back to check his handiwork. `` We do everything as if it were Day One of a war, except nobody shoots at us,'' <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON> explained after Thursday's flight. `` You really have a sense of urgency and mission in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces stationed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> are on increased alert in case communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> makes any attempt to disrupt the Olympic Games, which begin Sept. 17 in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is helping guarantee the security of the Olympics. <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON> and other pilots of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s 19th <ORGANIZATION> Tactical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> serve as forward air controllers whose mission is to spot and mark targets with smoke for other planes to attack. Their small planes also fly attack missions against ground targets. `` We control violence,'' is the motto worn by members of the squadron based at <ORGANIZATION> Osan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> south of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Hundreds of thousands of troops, including 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops, face each other in a tense confrontation on the Demilitarized Zone that divides the peninsula. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces have been based in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> since the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> intervened to help the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded in 1950 to begin the Korean War. An armistice was signed in 1953, but the north and south technically are still at war. Col. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, commander of the <ORGANIZATION> 5th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tactical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> threat is a daily fact of life. `` I think the threat presented by the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> is real. They are not what could be classified as rational actors,'' he said. South Korean and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commanders fear <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> will attempt to disrupt the Olympics because its demand to be a co-host of the Games has been rejected. The North has a long history of launching terrorist attacks against the South. `` The <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> would like to see an embarrassment to the Republic of -LRB- South -RRB- <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops wo n't be guarding Olympic venues, but the Games have increased the sense of tension and spurred greater vigilance, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said. `` Everyone's adrenalin goes up. Everyone leans forward in their foxholes,'' <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said. Airspace over <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and all Olympic sites has been declared off-limits during the Games. South Korean military air controllers quickly challenge any approaching plane. `` If you get real close to the capital area they threaten to shoot you down,'' <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON> said after being challenged by an air controller over the radio. <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON>, who has been stationed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> for three years, said training is intense because hostile forces are poised just a few miles away. Pilots carry war plans on all missions. `` We're ready to go to work at a moment's notice,'' he said. Flying over Nightmare Range about 15 miles from the border, <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON> pointed out a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> military air base visible across the border. `` The North Korean MiGs can be on us in two minutes,'' he said. <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON> said he has not seen a North Korean jet during his tour of duty in the South, but he and other pilots often hear the north's military radio traffic while they are flying. The airwaves along the border constantly crackle with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military air controllers giving instructions. The area routinely is busy with warplanes on patrol or practicing. South Koreans have to live with a constant military presence and frequent exercises that can be disruptive, but they accept the inconveniences as unavoidable, <PERSON> Vandervalk </PERSON> said. `` It shows how lucky people in the West are,'' he said. `` When was the last time an American had a tank roll through his garden?''
