<HEAD>Long-Awaited Inquest Into Gibraltar IRA Deaths To Begin</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When three <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> members were gunned down in <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> on March 6 while allegedly plotting a car bombing, the British government claimed a victory on the battlefield of terrorism. Instead it got a political controversy that is still simmering six months later. A long-awaited inquest into the killings opens Tuesday in the British colony on the southeast tip of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mairead </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> MacCann </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Savage </PERSON> were unarmed when they died. The car bomb, much to the British government's embarrassment, never materialized, although the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> admitted the three were on a guerrilla mission and a car full of explosives was found 40 miles from the scene two days later Moreover, two British television networks investigating what had happened that sunny Sunday in <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> found witnesses whose accounts strongly suggested the three were shot without being given any chance to surrender. It all boiled down to a simple question that confronts every democracy facing a terrorist threat: Did <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> bend the rule of law? Critics like <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the human rights watchdog, which demanded an inquiry into the shootings in hopes of answering that question, were rebuffed by Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who said she was outraged that the question was even being asked. As far as the government was concerned, a disaster was averted. It argued that there was no way of knowing on that day that no car bomb was in <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>; that it had to be assumed a bomb was set to blow up a military parade and hordes of onlooker