ION> men were gunned down in a British army ambush in the west of the province last Tuesday. Defending the government in the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> after the TV documentaries, Lord <PERSON> Chalfont </PERSON> denounced any `` equivalence between indiscriminate killing in the course of political terrorism, and the killing of terrorists by security forces engaged in counterterrorist operations.'' The liberal Guardian, on the other hand, maintained: `` A state that turns to terror itself in desperate recourse'' in the end endorses values of terrorists. Tuesday's inquest, which was postponed from June, is now the focus of attention. Sixty-five witnesses have been called, and <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> is in a state of high alert, wracked by frequent bomb scares. The seven operatives involved in the March 6 incident are thought to belong to the <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, a top-secret anti-terrorist team, and they will testify behind a screen to prevent their being marked for reprisals. But the British government has reserved the right to keep them away from the inquest. If the 11-member jury returns a verdict of unlawful killings, Attorney General <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Thistlethwaite </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> will prosecute the perpetrators, according to high-level sources in the colony who requested anonymity. The mainly <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> is fighting to end British rule in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> under socialist rule.
