 Here is a state-by-state look at the <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush-Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, based on an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> survey. Electoral College votes are in parenthesis, and it takes 270 to win. <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> -LRB- 9 -RRB- _ Southern edge to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> -LRB- 3 -RRB- _ One of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s strongest states. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> -LRB- 7 -RRB- _ Edge to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> -LRB- 6 -RRB- _ Close race. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> -LRB- 47 -RRB- _ Statistical dead heat in recent poll in the biggest state. <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> -LRB- 8 -RRB- _ Both sides see tough race but GOP sounds confident. <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> -LRB- 8 -RRB- _ <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> hopes to win next door to home state, but <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> has carried each time since 1968. <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> -LRB- 3 -RRB- _ Toss-up. District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> -LRB- 3 -RRB- _ Safe for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> -LRB- 21 -RRB- _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> holds advantage. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> -LRB- 12 -RRB- _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> holds edge. <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> -LRB- 4 -RRB- _ Should be <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> -LRB- 4 -RRB- _ Should be <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> -LRB- 24 -RRB- _ Both sides see initial <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> edge in key swing state. <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> -LRB- 12 -RRB- _ Safe for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in running mate <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s home state. <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> -LRB- 8 -RRB- _ Tight race but <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> rates early favorite. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> -L