<FIRST>r w PM-ThunderandLightning     09-05 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thunder and Lightning,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lightning Danger Greater Than Thunder Indicates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Both people and lightning-sensitive industries may be in more danger than they realize, according to a researcher who says the hazards of electrical storms have been underestimated. Lightning strikes the earth much more often than weather records based on observers' reports indicate, says <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Changnon </PERSON> in the Journal of Geophysical Research-Atmospheres. `` Those who have to worry about the risk of lightning damage, for example nuclear power plants, have had to use data based on -LRB- thunder records -RRB- to develop their risk analyses,'' Changnon said in a telephone interview. `` It's very clear that thunder rather dramatically underestimates the frequency of lightning near a given point.'' Changnon discovered by using electromagnetic detectors to record actual cloud-to-ground flashes that between 22 percent and 40 percent of lightning flashes occurred at times when no thunder was heard. `` It is not good news,'' he concluded. Changnon, a researcher affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION>, also teaches at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> His report was done in conjunction with his son, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Changnon </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyle </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>. Detailed thunderstorm records go back to the late 1800s, <PERSON> Changnon </PERSON> explained, but they have always depended on the reports of trained observers, primarily listening to the thunder generated by lightning. In recent years, however, electromagnetic detectors have been installed in many areas to record actual lightning strokes. The researchers compared reports by weather observers with the lightning records from sensors used by the federal <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> in Western states and by electrical utilities along the Eastern seaboard. `` The degree of relationship is relatively weak,'' Changnon reported. `` It gives one a lot of pause, in many respects, about how the atmosphere works, how good our weather records are and how safe we are.'' In the West, Changnon reported, between 31 percent and 40 percent of all lightning strokes were missed by observers listening for thunder. The situation was better in the East, with 22 percent to 26 percent of lightning strokes being missed, the report said. `` The differences are very marked between the East and West,'' Changnon said. This occurs, at least in part, because it is more difficult to hear thunder in mountainous areas, he said. Another batch of the missed lightning strokes occurs before a storm is reported in an area, he said. `` People sometimes say lightning comes out of the blue. It's not necessarily out of the blue, just the front edge of a new or fast-moving storm,'' he said. The study also confirmed that lightning varies considerably from storm to storm. More than half of all electrical storms had only a few cloud-to-ground lightning flashes, while a small number of storms had hundreds of strokes. Indeed, in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, records for three years showed that nearly one-quarter of all the lightning strokes were accounted for in just two big storms. The researchers also found a considerable number of thunderstorms with no cloud-to-ground lightning. Cloud-to-cloud lightning is blamed for the thunder in those cases. <PERSON> Changnon </PERSON> said that is more common in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, where storm clouds tend to be higher above the ground than in the East. Lightning killed 86 Americans last year, the highest death toll in this decade, according to records kept by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. And the 365 lightning-related injuries reported across the nation were nearly 50 percent more than the long-term average, the agency said. As usual, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> led the nation with 11 lightning deaths last year. <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> ranked second with six, followed by five in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and four each in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> each recorded three fatalities. There were two each in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> each recorded a single lightning death for the year.
</TEXT>
