<HEAD>Bite A Mistake, Owner Vows To Keep Pet Croc At Arms Length</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 71-year-old retiree whose pet crocodile bit off his arm was reunited with `` Charlene'' today and said he'd keep her _ at his other arm's length. `` Its marvellous having her back,'' said <PERSON> Alf </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>. `` The separation has n't changed us.'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Melbourne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> newspaper he thought his 23-year friendship with <PERSON> Charlene </PERSON>, a 6 -LCB- - foot saltwater croc, was doomed when she bit the arm that fed her Wildlife officers had wanted to shoot the reptile but <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s family intervened and <PERSON> Charlene </PERSON> was exiled to a crocodile farm in <LOCATION> Queensland </LOCATION> `` It was my fault. I asked her if she wanted some fish and I put my hand in the bucket and did n't give her a fish,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. `` All she could think about was the fish and with my hand being there she bit it.'' Despite losing his right arm and spending three weeks in the hospital after the November 1986 attack, <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said he always wanted <PERSON> Charlene </PERSON> back. `` I must admit I do keep her at arms length now, but I get in the pen with her and give her a bit of a scratch,'' he said. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> used to take <PERSON> Charlene </PERSON> on family outings and to the local pub until she got too heavy to handle, the newspaper said.
