<FIRST>r a PM-SuspendedAnimation     09-05 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Suspended Animation,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman In Suspended Animation For Nearly Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 76-year-old woman was placed in suspended animation nearly an hour as surgeons removed an egg-sized aneurysm from the base of her brain, hospital officials said. <PERSON> Cecilia </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> remained comatose Sunday and listed in critical condition, four days after the unusual operation, said <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Secreto </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. `` It's not uncommon for it to last a couple of days,'' Ms. <PERSON> Secreto </PERSON> said. Surgeons removed the aneurysm from Ms. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON>'s brain after dropping her body temperature by 40 degrees and draining the blood from her body. Her heart was stopped during Wednesday's operation. The coma was induced by barbiturates to protect the brain while blood flow was suspended, said Ms. <PERSON> Secreto </PERSON>. Dr. <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailes </PERSON>, a neurosurgeon, said Ms. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> fit the legal criteria for brain death during the 51 -LCB- minutes of suspended animation. The aneurysm, a bubble in the blood vessel caused by weakness in the vessel wall, was suctioned out while Ms. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> was on the bypass machine. Any more pressure by the aneurysm would have compressed on the vital centers of the brain stem, and her heart would have stopped or she would have gone into a coma and died, <PERSON> Bailes </PERSON> said. `` I'm still worried about her but, objectively speaking, there is a good chance she may pull through this thing,'' he said. Post-surgical scans showed increased brain activity, and Ms. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> was moving her legs when touched, according to <PERSON> Bailes </PERSON>. But, he said, `` There's such a fine line between a perfect outcome and her never waking up. That's the hard thing.'' Ms. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> had