<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Fall In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Both the dollar and stock prices lost ground in cautious trading in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today. The dollar opened at 136.25 yen, down 0.50 yen from Friday's close, and then declined further to end the day at 136.03 yen, down 0.72 yen The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency ranged between 135.95 yen and 136.35 yen, with spot trading estimated at $ 4.4 billion. It was the first day-to-day decline in the dollar in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> since last Monday. Foreign exchange traders were in a cautious mood because the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> market was closed for the Labor Day holiday, said a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` In addition, today is Monday, when trading usually gets cautious, which makes it even harder for investors to figure out which direction the market is going to go,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` That's why the dollar-yen exchange rate changed frequently within a narrow range,'' he added. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which gained 371.75 points during Saturday's half-day session, lost 146.67 points, or 0.53 percent, closing at 27,341.58 Although the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index opened the day strongly, it then reversed directions as trading slowed down. `` The dollar-yen rate, which is getting stable, and the increased <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jobless rate made investors less worried about inflation, but they could n't be completely optimistic yet,'' said <PERSON> Yoshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Shimoyama </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` After the active trading in the early morning, some inve