f the rival <LOCATION> Crips </LOCATION> and Bloods vowed to lay down their guns, end their gang affiliations and form a network to convince other `` homeboys'' to do the same. `` We have intelligence and want a quality education. I know that we're running out of time ... <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, listen today,'' said gang member <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> <PERSON> Bay </PERSON>, who attended the summit. Officials criticized the summits for giving a false impression of optimism because the small number of gang members participating do n't represent the 70,000 members from the 600 street gangs. But organizers say at least they're doing something. Officials also cautioned it will be a long time before the programs and law enforcment efforts take effect. `` Be patient a little longer,'' said Sgt. <PERSON> Wes </PERSON> <PERSON> McBride </PERSON> of the county sheriff's department. `` It will change. We'll get a handle on it, but it wo n't be an overnight thing. We will win. We will finally beat them down.''
