<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> today began his first trip to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, a five-day visit expected to include discussions on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concerns about <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> arms sales in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carlucci </LOCATION> is to hold talks on global, regional and bilateral issues with his host, National Defense Minister <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Qiwei </PERSON>. He is also scheduled to meet <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s top leader, <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, and Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>. He spent two days in <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> before flying to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, where he was met at the airport by Gen. <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> <PERSON> Wenzhong </PERSON>, head of the bureau of foreign affairs in the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> is expected to restate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concerns about <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s arms sales to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> says could destabilize military balances in that volatile region. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has reportedly sold Silkworm anti-ship missiles to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and recently agreed to supply <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> with medium-range surface-to-surface missiles. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is also trying to sell to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> a shorter-range missile now under development. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which denies selling Silkworms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, is building up its arms industry to help finance the modernization of its own armed forces. When Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> brought up the issue of <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> sales during a visit in July, the Chinese said the weapons were of a defensive nature and the sales carried out in a responsible manner. Chinese officials are, in turn, likely to urge <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to ease restrictions on sales of high technology items to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The Chinese say <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businessmen are losing business to Japanese and European competitors because the Pentagon is reluctant to allow transfer of some types of technology. In particular, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is expected to urge the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to give the go-ahead for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies to use Chinese Long March rockets to launch satellites. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is to make a decision on the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> launches later this month. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has recommended that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> grant export licenses for the satellites, but the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has objected, saying that would undercut <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies trying to develop satellite launching services. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s visit is the third by a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> chief during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, following visits by former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> in 1983 and 1986. Visits and personnel exchanges between the militaries of the two countries have become common, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military sales to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have grown at a steady if modest pace. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has supplied <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with transport helicopters and avionics equipment for Chinese fighter planes, and <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> is now holding negotiations on possible sales of about a dozen CH-47 helicopters for use in a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> rapid deployment force. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> is also to travel to the ancient capital of <LOCATION> Xian </LOCATION> and stop in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, where he will tour a Chinese naval facility.
