<HEAD>Sam White, Veteran Paris Correspondent, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Australian journalist <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> correspondent for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> newspaper for more than 40 years, has died in the French capital at age 77. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, his daughter-in-law, said the journalist died Sunday in a clinic where he was receiving treatment for respiratory problems. White continued his weekly column until shortly before his death. During World War II, White reported for <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sydney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION>. He covered in the 1944 invasion of <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> and entered <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. After the war, <PERSON> White </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> Austrialia </LOCATION> briefly but soon came back to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He began working for the Evening Standard in 1947. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, he became a familiar sight in the Crillon bar, where he had his own telephone, and visiting journalists were often taken there to be introduced to him. Later, the <ORGANIZATION> Travelers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> became his base. Despite his inability to master the French language, <PERSON> White </PERSON> had an extraordinary range of contacts in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and regaled his readers with a column of gossip about society, the arts and the underworld, combined with shrewd analysis of French politics. He also wrote for the British weekly Spectator and visited <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> occasionally to watch cricket at Lord's. White was born in <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, from which his family fled during the Bolshevik Revolution to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, settling in <LOCATION> Melbourne </LOCATION>. He was educated at <ORGANIZATION> Melbourne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and joined the <ORGANIZATION> Australian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, but was expelled for `` bourgeois bohemianism.'' He came to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> at the end of the 1930s. White had two sons by his first marriage and a daughter by his second.
