 Three governors met with <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> officials today and appealed for more Japanese investment in their states to help with economic hardship. <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Mississipi </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> said their states had been hit by declines in manufacturing and the oil industry, but were rich in assets that the Japanese need. The three Democrats met with Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> to urge increased Japanese investment, and also met with officials of the <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> External Trade Organization, the Japan-Southern <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, and officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Export-Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said the tri-state region is rich in oil and natural gas, timber, agricultural products and seafood, all products <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> needs and that can be transported through the states' six seaports. <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> said the states are interested in attracting Japanese chemical, electronics and auto parts manufacturers. Although the three states already attract more than $ 20 billion in foreign investments _ most of it from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ almost none comes from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Mississipi </LOCATION> is offering incentives such as property tax exemptions, low-interest or no-interest loans and tax credits for high-technology jobs. `` We can build roads, railroads, and ports at state expense. We have a number of buildings ready to be leased or purchased,'' he added. <PERS