<HEAD>50-Block Power Outage Ends In Downtown Seattle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Power was restored to all but one building today in a 50-block area of downtown that was left without electricity for three days by a fire in underground feeder cables. <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> City Light workers completed repairs to a fifth 13,000-volt cable Sunday night, utility spokesman <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Forslund </PERSON> said. Repairs to the sixth and last burned out cable should be completed today, he said. Until the sixth cable is back in service, many buildings will have only partial power because they are served by a combination of the repaired and unrepaired cables, said <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON> of City Light. The last building without service was a parking garage with some office space near the fire site, <PERSON> Forslund </PERSON> said. Frozen food thawed, elevators would n't budge and air conditioners were useless during one of the hottest weeks in city history after service was cut Wednesday by a fire in an underground transformer and switching vault. About half the affected customers began getting power Saturday evening when the switch was thrown on four repaired feeder cables and other customers were hooked up during the night. The cause of the outage was undetermined but City Light superintendent <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> said the fire apparently started in the municipal utility's cables. Power to those feeders should have been cut by current limiters that act when a cable gets hot. In addition, power continued flowing through an adjacent aluminum supply cable for overhead electrical trolley bus lines. That cable melted, `` so what you had was molten aluminum cutting our cables'' <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> said Sunday night. Had it not been for the lack of a power cutoff on the transit cable, <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> said, it would have been `` a two-building outage of a day or so.'' As power restoration began, fire crews roamed the area to make sure no fires were triggered in equipment left switched on when the outage began. `` It went very smoothly. I have no reports of problems other than the sprinker in the Battery Street tunnel,'' which apparently began wetting down the tunnel when it was tripped by the power surge, <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON> said. `` We called the fire department and told them it was their problem.'' At the <ORGANIZATION> Westin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION>, full service was restored to the 40-story south tower early Sunday, while the 47-story north tower remained on a diesel generator, rented for $ 6,200 a week, marketing director <PERSON> Dell </PERSON> <PERSON> Schooly </PERSON> said. City Light officials had no estimate of costs to restore power or repair damage, but <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON> said he understood the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> would consider a special appropriation. During the height of the blackout, city officials estimated that 90 percent of all businesses were closed in the area, which has an estimated 130 restaurants, 55 shops in the popular Pike Place Market, the <LOCATION> Bon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marche </LOCATION> department store and uncounted hotels, grocery stores and taverns. The blackout coincided with a heat wave in which Friday's temperature was 98 degrees, a record for September, and Saturday's high 92, a record for the Sunday was in the low 80s.
