<HEAD>Mail Strike Spreads In Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of British postal workers were on strike today, halting some 100 million letters and parcels, in a work stoppage over regional bonuses and the hiring of temporary workers. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, said more than 40,000 of its members in the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> were striking Sunday and the whole system could be brought to a halt by midweek. The Post Office, which employs 140,000 people and handles 51 million items a day, said 28 major city center sorting offices were on strike, affecting 100 million letters and parcels. In affected areas, mail can not be collected, sorted or delivered. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION> are among the affected cities. Overseas mail has almost stopped because the two sorting offices which handle it are on strike. The postal strike began Wednesday as a 24-hour walkout to protest regional pay bonuses _ an issue that remains unresolved. The strike has continued in various parts of the country to protest the bonuses and the hiring of temporary workers to clear the backlog of mail caused by Wednesday's strike. The union objects to the Post Office offering weekly bonuses of 7.5 pounds to 20 pounds -LRB- $ 12.52 to $ 33.40 -RRB- to recruit workers in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and southeast <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Those regions are prosperous, and the postal service has difficulty hiring workers. The union said it would not tolerate regional pay differences and any bonuses should be paid nationally.
