 The <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> voted overwhelmingly today to expel the electricians' union, its first ouster of an affiliate in 15 years. Delegates of the electricians' 336,000-member union showed their disdain by walking out en masse minutes before the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> took its vote. The vote, by a show of hands, came on the opening morning of the Trades Union's week-long annual conference in this south <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> seaside resort. The Electronic, <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plumbing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> was ousted for signing two single-union no-strike deals with management in violation of Trades Union policy. More than 30 single-union no-strike deals have been struck in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, with one union representing all the workers at a plant and disputes submitted to binding arbitration. The Trades Union believes such deals weaken union bargaining power and lead to competition among unions for representation in a shrinking job market. Some predicted the expulsion would create a ripple effect, confronting the 9-million member national labor federation with what <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> called the `` most serious split in British trade union history.'' It also raised the prospect of the electricians and other rebellious unions forming a rival labor federation. Among those siding with the electricians' union is the <ORGANIZATION> Amalgamated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>'s second biggest affiliate. Delegates shouted down engineers' leader <PERSON> Bill </PERSO