<HEAD>Israeli Settlers Devise Security Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Israel-Politics, Bjt
^By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLON SHEVUT, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To protect themselves from Palestinian stone-throwers, Jewish settlers operate a radio warning system and community patrols and even train bus operators to shoot while driving. Many settlers are dissatisfied with army security and their anger has grown along with the number of Palestinian attacks on their settlements during the 9-month-old uprising, which has killed four Israelis and nearly 260 Arabs. On Sunday, 200 settlers protested outside government offices where the Cabinet was discussing whether to allow them to open fire more freely on the stone-throwers. Authorities have said civilians may open fire only when their lives are in imminent danger. Military jeeps escort local buses on their way through Palestinian towns and refugee camps, sites of frequent rock-throwing attacks, and soldiers patrol the areas. But many residents say present defenses are not enough and have set up their own forms of protection. A radio attack warning center that covers 15 settlements with a population of 10,000 is housed in the basement of the regional council in <LOCATION> Gush </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Etzion </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Shilo </LOCATION> Gal, chairman of the council. The center is staffed round-the-clock by reserve soldiers, most of whom are local residents. Small settlements are guarded by one or two armed settlers, while larger communities are patrolled by jeeps with sirens and radios, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bedein </PERSON>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> settlers' spokesman. <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> showed how Jewish bus drivers in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> are being taught self-defense, including driving around roadblocks, helping passengers to jump through bus windows during a firebomb attack and caring for the wounded. The program showed bus drivers firing pistols from moving vehicles and trying to drive without flinching while tennis balls were thrown at their windshield to simulate rock attacks. <PERSON> Gal </PERSON> said the windows of the buses are being covered with metal grills. `` We ca n't trust the army and it wo n't allow us to protect ourselves and our children,'' said <PERSON> Yisrael </PERSON> <PERSON> Maler </PERSON> of the Teqoa settlement. `` Last Friday, we had to wait for 45 minutes for the escort. We returned to the bus station, called the army and waited for another 45 minutes. Not one of us had a gun.'' Meanwhile, soldiers `` just stand around, look at stone-throwers and smoke cigarettes,'' said the Soviet-born <PERSON> Maler </PERSON>, who moves around with an army-issued M-16 rifle. Some of the other settlers carry pistols. Some legislators have expressed concern that settlers given a green light to fire on stone-throwers would shoot indiscriminately. The debate was heightened after a settler accidentally shot and wounded two soldiers last week when he opened fire at a Palestinian who threw a firebomb that missed his car. But Shilo Gal says the settlers must rely on government patrols and organized defenses. `` We can not do more because people would accuse us of forming militias,'' he said.
