<HEAD>Americans Help Bring Order to Liberia's Financial Chaos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite initial skepticism, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials are pleased with an experiment in which 17 American financial experts moved into <LOCATION> Liberian </LOCATION> government offices to bring order to the African nation's chaotic financial system. <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, a country founded by freed <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> slaves a century and a half ago, has always had a special relationship with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and President <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doe </PERSON> turned to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1987 after his fiscal problems ran out of control. Corruption was rampant, government checks were bouncing, civil servants were being paid months late and bureaucrats were spending money without regard to budgetary limits. Some government contractors were not paid for work performed while others received checks they were not entitled to. In January, 1987, when Secetary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> made a brief stop in <LOCATION> Monrovia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Doe </PERSON> told him, `` I need help.'' The two countries worked out a plan to put American accountants, systems managers and computer experts _ recruited by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> _ inside the <LOCATION> Liberian </LOCATION> bureaucracy. The `` operational experts'' _ nicknamed `` Opex'' _ assumed their duties in January. Nine of the 17 went to the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's worked reasonably well,'' one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, summing up the eight-month-old experiment. `` The benefits have been considerable already.'' The official, who insisted on anonymity, said the two-year program `` has exceeded the expectations of a lot of people who thought it would never get off the ground.'' Among other benefits, civil servants are now being paid on time, he said. Another official, also speaking anonymously, said, `` Before there was no government budget. Everything was entirely ad hoc. Opex has gotten the Liberians to adhere to the budget. It's under pretty good control but there are still some financial flows outside the budget.'' With the Americans co-signing checks and taking over much of <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>'s economic management, the plan gives the appearance of a Liberian surrender of sovereignty in a key area, which is a complaint voiced by Liberian opposition leaders. But the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says <PERSON> Doe </PERSON> still has the final say on all financial matters. <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> may be the only country where it would be politically possible for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to play such an intrusive role. But <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, with its red, white and blue flag and its use of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar as legal tender, has always looked on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as a friend and patron. The financial crisis can be traced back about 10 years when the <LOCATION> Liberian </LOCATION> government decided to build a $ 200 million convention center it could n't afford. The country fell deeply into debt, and the problems were compounded in 1980 when <PERSON> Doe </PERSON>, then a 28-year-old sergeant, took power in a military coup, bringing with him a team of advisers with no government experience. As prices of <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>'s principal exports fell, foreign exchange earnings dropped. Eventually, because of a poor debt repayment record, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> declared <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> ineligible for new loans. Now, as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials describe it, <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>'s future seems brighter, and not only because of Opex. Human rights violations are down, <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>'s press is once again one of the freest in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and there is increased demand for international demand for latex, <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>'s major export. Concern about AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ has touched off a boom in sales of latex products, such as condoms and gloves, contributing to the more upbeat mood these days among Liberians.
