<FIRST>u w AM-DrugBill Bjt   09-05 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Bill, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Something For Everybody, Democrats And Republicans Alike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democratic leadership has stamped a showcase drug-fighting bill `` bipartisan,'' and is trying to secure <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> support by permitting votes on conservative-inspired issues like the death penalty. The strategy, devised by Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, could produce an overwhelming majority for legislation that incumbents from both parties could use in their election races. Debate begins Wednesday, and a final vote could take place Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will then follow with its own drug bill and the two versions would eventually be merged into final legislation. The bipartisan approach could blunt any Republican plans to paint Democrats as soft on crime _ a theme already sounded by Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I do n't think being tough on drugs means Republicans,'' said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Whip <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., `` Many Democrats feel just as strongly as Republicans, because we think it's right. House Republicans, on the other hand, wo n't have to rant and rave as they often do that Democrats use the rules to keep <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> proposals from <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> votes. They'll have guaranteed votes on amendments that advance their political agenda. Many Democrats may join them in some votes. The key issues will be a federal death penalty, denial of federal benefits and state driver's licenses to drug users, and a `` good faith'' exception to admit illegally seized drug evidence. The House bill as introduced carries a $ 1.5 billion to $ 2 billion annual pricetag, money that would be added to the $ 3.9 billion a year the federal government is now spending to fight drug abuse. The legislation includes something for everyone involved in fighting illegal drugs: more money for education, treatment and rehabilitation; and more resources for state and local law enforcement efforts to seize drugs on land, in the air and on the seas. But there also are new twists, such as controlling the U.S.-made chemicals that find their way to foreign cocaine laboratories, and old controversies, like gun control. The bill contains a seven-day waiting period for handgun purchasers that has become the latest cause for both the gun owner and pro-regulation groups. Gun control organizations argue that a national waiting period would make it more difficult for drug dealers to obtain handguns, mainly in the 28 states that now have no waiting period. Pro-gun organizations protest that only law-abiding citizens would be harmed by the delay, because criminals would not go to legitimate dealers. The key <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> amendments would: _ Provide a mandatory death penalty against those who commit murder in the course of a federal drug felony One liberal Democratic alternative calls for mandatory life imprisonment. _ Allow admission in court of improperly seized drug evidence if law enforcement officers acted in `` good faith. _ Deny student loans, <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> mortgages, rent subsidies and other federal benefits to convicted drug users until they complete rehabilitation programs After rehabilitation, benefits would be reinstated. Another GOP-sponsored amendment, which some Republicans oppose, would require the revocation or suspension of a driver's license for those convicted of a drug-related offense. Federal money would be withheld from states to force compliance. Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION> and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> select committee on narcotics, said he does n't care much for the bipartisan approach. `` Once the leadership said ` bipartisan,' the Republicans wanted these draconian measures,'' he said. <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> said that for conservatives, `` the litmus test for commitment is the federal death penalty.'' The death penalty now is applied only for state crimes, because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has not adopted the constitutional standards required to carry out capital punishment. However, <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> predicted that many Democrats would back the death penalty and suggested the main party split would come over the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> plan to deny benefits to drug users. To address complaints from local officials who said they never received promised anti-drug grants, the bill would require states to automatically pass through anti-drug money to local governments. Banking law revisions would allow the government to closely watch institutions where drug money might be laundered. Recipients of federal grants or contracts would need to maintain a drug-free workplace. Money would be provided for drug education, treatment and rehabilitation for AIDS victims and groups with a high risk of getting the disease. The legislation would authorize $ 10 million for a Latin American regional anti-drug force if one is approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
