<SECOND>AM-China-Law,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislature Approves China's First State Secret Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature approved the nation's first law to protect state secrets, a strict regulation that stipulates life sentences and even the death penalty for violators, it was announced Monday. The law was adopted Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which handles the day-to-day affairs of the congress, the <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said. The panel then adjourned a weeklong meeting. The 35-article law protects national security and obliges all citizens and organizations to keep state secrets. The law will go into effect in May, replacing provisional regulations on state secrets that were issued in 1951. The Xinhua dispatch defined state secrets as `` important decisions of national defense, diplomatic affairs, secret affairs concerning the national economic and social development and science and technology and activities related to state safety and to the investigation of crime.'' The law divides state secrets into three categories: strictly confidential, confidential and secret. Disclosure of strictly confidential information would seriously damage state safety and interests, it said. Those who steal, secretly gather, buy or illegally provide state secrets to foreigners or foreign institutions will be sentenced to between five and 10 years in prison for minor cases. In extremely serious cases, the sentence is a minimum of 10 years, life imprisonment or the death penalty, <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said.
