<FIRST>r a AM-Airline'sDemise     09-05 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airline's Demise,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Provincetown-Boston, Nation's Oldest Commuter Airline, Officially
Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Provincetown-Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's first regional commuter carrier and once the largest, officially dies Tuesday. In reality, it died four years ago. `` What's happening now is like watching a patient catching cancer,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsdale </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who had to resign as <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> stripped his pilot's license in disastrous 1984 `` When the patient dies, it's merciful. Some industry analysts say the demise of the 39-year-old airline is an example of how deregulation has crippled small commuter airlines, partly by spurring fare wars and unchecked growth. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsdale </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON> started the carrier on Nov. 30, 1949, with just a two-seat Cessna 140. Over the years, <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION> routinely ran extra planes to <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION> and area resort islands if more passengers showed up, and it grew in the early 1980s after <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsdale </PERSON> turned control over to his expansion-minded sons. Then came back-to-back fatal accidents in 1984. The federal government shut down the airline because of safety and training violations. Two weeks after it was flying again, 13 people died in a crash in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Bankruptcy and takeover followed close behind. The bitter <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsdale </PERSON> sons say the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> overreacted to minor problems. The father says his sons too brashly expanded what was a cozy and profitable regional service. `` We did n't overreact at all,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON>. `` We reacted properly and in the interest of aviation safety.'' <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION> formally ceases to be an airline Tuesday when its parent, <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harbor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Bangor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, a tiny part of the giant <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, retires its federal operating certificate. <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION>'s planes are being sold _ including N136PB, a DC-3 flying since the durable breed went out of production in the 1940s _ and service on some routes will be reduced or canceled, <LOCATION> Bar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> sales director <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said. `` You might lay the whole thing at the door of deregulation,'' said <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurdle </PERSON>, associate editor of Travel Weekly, who has written about <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION>. `` <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsdale </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> was worried about the competitive effects of deregulation, so he expanded arguably more than he should have.'' Over the years, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsdale </PERSON> conservatively expanded service. In the late 1950s, he worked out a innovative deal with <ORGANIZATION> Naples </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> under which the two carriers borrowed each other's services in the off-season; <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION> sent its planes and crews north in the summer, while <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION>'s operations migrated south in winter. Then he retired in 1980, turning <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION> over to his sons, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who bought more planes, acquired another small airline and bulked up operations. Flights were added around <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and the South. `` I had reservations,'' said the elder <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsdale </PERSON>, 68. `` I felt they were moving a little too fast. On the other hand, everything seemed to be going well.'' By 1983, <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION> was the largest regional commuter in the nation. It carried 220,000 passengers in 1979 and saw its load grow six times to 1.3 million in the first nine months of 1984, a period in which <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION> reported profits of $ 3.3 million on revenues of $ 58.4 million. By the end of 1984, <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION> had 1,600 employees, 500 daily flights and 104 planes. `` In order to survive in a deregulated environment we had to grow,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 43. `` They were the envy of some carriers for some time because they made money,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based aviation consultant. Then came the crashes and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> scrutiny. Public confidence collapsed. Passenger traffic dropped 50 percent in two days, bankers tightened the reins on more than $ 30 million in credit, the stock plummeted. <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION> filed for bankruptcy in March 1985. A year later it was bought for $ 30 million by <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, itself now defunct. <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> economics professor who headed the now-defunct <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> when it deregulated the industry in 1978, disagrees that deregulation is to blame for <ORGANIZATION> PBA </ORGANIZATION>'s collapse `` Deregulation gave people an opportunity to make money, as some of them have,'' he said, `` and gave other people a chance to make mistakes.''
