<HEAD>White Law Lecturer Freed After More Than Two Years in Detention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON>, a law school lecturer jailed without charge longer than any other white activist, was freed Monday after more than two years in detention but was placed under heavy restrictions. <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON>, 43, was detained June 12, 1986, the day that President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> declared a nationwide state of emergency that remains in effect. <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON> spent much of his detention in solitary confinement and was allowed a half-hour visit from his brother or sister every two weeks. A restriction order issued by Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> places <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON> under nighttime house arrest and bars him from any educational facility, effectively preventing him from returning to his job at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON> was being released on `` humanitarian grounds'' because his health had deteriorated in recent weeks. The statement did not elaborate. <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON>, wearing blue jeans and a blue sweatshirt, had a tearful reunion with his sister and his friends at a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> house where he will be required to spend each night. Atop his shoulder was a small lovebird he had been allowed to keep in his cell at <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> Prison. Friends said three months ago <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON> was allowed to keep a bird, but the first died, and the second escaped, even though its wings had been clipped. His restriction order requires him to report twice daily to the neighborhood police station, forbids him from leaving <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and bars him from giving interviews, according to his lawyers. They said <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON> also is barred from working with various anti-apartheid organizations and can not have more than four visitors at his house at one time. An estimated 30,000 people, virtually all of them black, have been detained for varying periods during the emergency. The government does not issue comprehensive statistics on detentions. Last week, it said there were 802 detainees still in custody who had been held longer than 30 days. <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON>, a law lecturer at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, served eight years in prison starting in 1975 for aiding the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement. In March 1985, he was elected to the <ORGANIZATION> Transvaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> executive committee of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a non-banned nationwide anti-apartheid coalition. In 1986, he co-authored a book about the Freedom Charter, a blueprint for a non-racial, post-apartheid <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> that has been endorsed by the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Suttner </PERSON> was detained at <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>'s airport as he was about to fly to <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, to deliver lectures about the Freedom Charter and popular justice.
