<HEAD>Worst Of Drought Is Over For Mississippi River, But Problems
Linger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shipping companies, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> are joining in an unprecedented effort to ensure that the drought-caused bottlenecks that idled <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> traffic this summer wo n't recur, a shipping industry executive says. The three groups are forming a task force and establishing a clearinghouse at <LOCATION> Cincinnait </LOCATION> to share information about the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rivers </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, vice president of a shipping industry group called American Waterway Operators. The drought, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said, has cost the industry an estimated $ 200 million, about 20 percent of its annual operating revenue. However, the worst of the 1988 drought may be past for those who work on or live along the river, some officials believe. An underwater dike built by the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, for example, has stopped saltwater from creeping up the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and fouling the water supply for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. However, the Corps has had to supply by barge some downriver communities with millions of gallons of fresh water. At <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, the river is running at a rate of about 130,000 cubic feet per second _ about 55 percent of normal for this time of year. In early July, however, it was closer to 114,000. `` We're still way below average,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Steakely </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, Miss. `` But we're not nearly as bad as we were.'' Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> waters have pushed their way up the drought-reduced river, turning the muddy, brown water a beautiful blue-green and threatening the water supply for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, which is about 100 miles from the mouth of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. Because the salty water is heavier than the fresh <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> water, the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> decided to impede the flow by building a dirt dam 15 to 25 feet high across the river bottom. The $ 790,000 structure, about 30 miles south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, succeeded in heading off the salty flow. It was too late, however, for some small communities in <LOCATION> Plaquemines </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> continues to deliver barge-loads of water from farther upriver. By the middle of last week, the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> had barged 52 million gallons for those communities, according to <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Sossaman </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> office of the Corps. The increased flow on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> also means a reduction in the number of bottlenecks that idled traffic upriver in June. Last week, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> relaxed restrictions on towboat loads that had been imposed earlier this summer because of low water levels on the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. The task of the clearinghouse on river conditions is to ensure that everyone on the river is informed of current developments, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` It's a matter of the industry and the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and the Corps working smarter,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` They took all the communications that were disparate and decentralized, and centralized them out of one office on the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>.'' As for how long the drought will affect the rivers, the experts are n't sure. `` Based on what the weather service has said, there's virtually no way we're going to get back to normal ... We've been hearing we're in for drought conditions on the river through the remainder of the summer,'' said <PERSON> Sossaman </PERSON>. The amount of rain needed to bring the river back up to its average flow rate may not come around until next spring, <PERSON> Steakely </PERSON> said. And that's all right with him. A sudden heavy flow of water down the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> would dump more sand and sediment down river and could cause as many problems with navigation as it would solve, <PERSON> Steakely </PERSON> said. Slow, steady improvement is better, he said. `` We really are n't hoping for a dramatic change quickly.
