<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 All the trustees of a private elementary school wanted was a new gymnasium, a library and room for more offices. What Trinity School got was more like a castle. `` Kindergothic'' is the word coined by architects <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sargent </PERSON> and <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> to describe an architectural style that combines a crystal-studded rock wall and turret rising from a ravine. The front entrance is sheltered by skewed columns of stacked stone cubes. `` It's architecture for children without being ridiculous,'' <PERSON> Sargent </PERSON> said. `` We used details in an informal way so children could look at it and actually learn something about architecture.'' Passersby are startled but children are delighted. `` There's a whimsical quality about the new structures that at first rocks the adult back a little bit, but the children ... see it as they might imagine a castle would be like ... -LRB- filled with -RRB- all kinds of strange windows and beautifully colored objects,'' said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, headmaster at Trinity throughout the project.
