<HEAD>Archbishop Denounces Police Response to Bomb Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> criticized police Monday for suggesting that a bomb blast at the headquarters of several anti-apartheid groups was caused by explosives stored in the building. Police officials made the suggestion last week following the Aug. 31 explosion that wrecked <ORGANIZATION> Khotso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a six-story office building in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> used by the South African Council of Churches and several human rights groups. Police said investigators had been unable to get through the rubble to the section of an underground garage where the bomb was believed to have been placed. But they suggested explosives were being stored in the building for use elsewhere. Building occupants said they believe the bombers were right-wing extremists or even security force members. `` The police have implied that those who work in <LOCATION> Khotso </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION> are perpetrators of violence,'' said <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, leader of the Anglican church in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` It is an absolutely disgraceful suggestion to make, and it is made worse by the fact the police have made it without a tittle of evidence and before doing any proper investigation,'' <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> said in a statement. `` We are still waiting to hear the government's clear condemnation of the bombing.'' He said the bombing should be viewed in the context of a claim by military commanders last week that the army was beyond the jurisdiction of the courts because <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> was in a state of war. On Sunday, <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> deliberately defied a government ban on calls for voting boycotts, urging blacks and whites to stay away from the polls in next month's nationwide municipal elections. State-of-emergency regulations provide for a jail sentence of up to 10 years for promoting election boycotts.