<HEAD>LaserPhoto XACC1,XACC2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Longtime watchers of the Miss America Pageant may notice a few changes during Saturday's contest, including `` swimsuit strolls'' and an `` improved'' final crowning moment. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON>, the production manager for the <ORGANIZATION> Miss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pageant </ORGANIZATION>, has been testing new ideas in local contests in the past year. Other changes will be a deeper set on the stage and a Y-shaped runway `` that will give us more flexibility in production numbers,'' <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON> said during a rehearsal break last week. But a more daring innovation is in the swimsuit competition, he said. `` Instead of standing in front of the judges and ` ankling up,' as we called it, we're going to have the girls do a ` walking turn' and not stop at all,'' <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON> said `` We're de-emphasizing that ` inspection' image that it had for so long.'' The changes in this year's pageant, scheduled to be televised nationally by <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, came largely from `` brainstorming'' sessions held in the past year after the appointment of the pageant's new executive director, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>. <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON> recalled that <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> almost immediately came in and listed all the things he did n't like about the pageant production in years past. `` It's exciting _ there's a lot of change,'' <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON> said. `` We're going back to the days when the top contestants were asked questions on stage _ and these wo n't be ` airhead' questions.'' <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> said the questions `` will be intelligent questions. We're not going to be testing them on current events, but they wo n't be silly questions either. The final moments of the competition will also be different than in recent years, <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON> said. Traditionally, the fourth, third, second and first runners-up were announced, and then the new Miss <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was announced from the remaining six contestants. This year, the fourth, third and second runners-up will be announced, and then, to heighten the drama, the remaining six contestants will be narrowed down to two. The first runner-up will then be announced, leaving the new Miss <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON> said. `` The interplay between the two young ladies promises to be good,'' he said. `` We've tested this in some of the states and it's worked well. The pageant production will also have one fewer song-and-dance number, <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON> said. `` The show is supposed to focus on 51 young, talented ladies, so we're including them in all the production numbers,'' he said. The time saved from dropping that number will allow the producer to include brief video spots of the top 10 finalists' interviews before the judges, <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON> said. `` I got the idea to include parts of the contestants' interviews from the Winter Olympics, when we saw some backstage interviews before the athlete went out on the ice or snow,'' he said. The `` Miss America Moments'' that used to come before each commercial break _ which simply told viewers what part of the contest was next _ will be replaced with short spots on what former state winners are now doing, <PERSON> Caligari </PERSON> said. Some of those women include a town mayor, an assistant district attorney, a Broadway understudy and an aeronautical engineer, he said.
