federation; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than one-quarter of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s postal workers walked off their jobs Monday as a nationwide mail strike spread and prevented the delivery of 65 million foreign and domestic letters and parcels. Three postal workers were arrested in <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION>, one of 40 cities where sorting offices were paralyzed by the strikes by 48,000 workers, said the national post office, Royal Mail. Royal Mail, which handles 51 million items of mail daily, said the three were charged with disorderly behavior after bottles were thrown from a picket line at arriving temporary workers. It was the first instance of violence in six days of strikes that began Wednesday with a 24-hour strike to protest regional pay differences. The one-day strike officially ended, but the issue of temporary workers hired to clear backlogs has continued to keep workers away from their jobs. On Monday, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION> were among cities where mail could not be collected, posted, sorted or delivered due to walkouts by 48,000 of 140,000 sorting and collecting workers. Stamps could be purchased because 40,000 administration and counter workers have not gone on strike. International mail was completely suspended `` until further notice'' after walkouts at sorting offices for foreign mail in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and other cities, said post office spokeswoman <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said although workers at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> airport office had gone back to work, other offices were not in operation. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cockburn </PERSON>, managing director of <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION>, defended the hiring of 3,500