<HEAD>Non-Aligned Proposal Calls For Sanctions Against Israel, South
Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign ministers preparing Monday for the non-aligned movement conference discussed proposals that contain sanctions against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The five-day conference of foreign ministers is to chart the 101-member organization's role over the next decade. Organizers said 92 members plan to attend, including 70 foreign ministers. President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassilou </PERSON> formally opens the three-day conference on Wednesday. But delegates on Monday began considering a 60-page draft resolution dealing with international problems. The draft sharply criticizes <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, echoing previous sentiments of the movement. A copy of the draft notes that since the non-aligned summit conference last year the situation in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> `` has worsened considerably, particularly as a result of the actions of the Israeli occupation forces against the civilian population in the occupied territories.'' The draft `` salutes the heroic uprising of the Palestinian people,'' in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. It says the Arab uprising in the occupied lands that began Dec. 8 is `` tangible evidence of their determination to have a state of their own.'' It demands <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> sanctions against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The draft also expresses `` profound alarm at the sharp deterioration of the situation in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'' and repeats previous demands for sanctions against the South African government, which is controlled by the country's white minority. The resolution expresses satisfaction with the July 20 cease-fire between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and states the U.N.-mediated peace talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> should lead to a `` a comprehensive and lasting solution'' in the 8-year-old war between the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> rivals. The draft makes no reference to Iraqi use of chemical weapons in the war. Conference sources speaking on condition of anonymity said Iranian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> is expected to demand <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s condemnation on that issue when he addresses the conference on Wednesday. More than 1,500 police officers, including special anti-terrorist units, have been assigned to guard the conference center where the meeting is being held and the delegates' hotels.
