<HEAD>Dollar Steadies After Friday's Falls; Gold Slightly Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar opened lower today after losing ground Friday on higher-than-expected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment data. Gold was slightly weaker. Trading on European markets was lulled by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Labor Day holiday, dealers said. The dollar had fallen sharply on Friday after news that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment rate had risen to 5.6 percent from 5.4 percent in July. It lost more than a pfennig against the West German mark, a centime against the Swiss franc and 1 -LCB- cents against the Dutch guilder. Traders said they expected the dollar to hold steady through today, but dealers in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> forecast a lower dollar in the medium term. `` We expect a further decline this week,'' said one dealer at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.72 yen to a closing 136.03. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 135.65 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.8525 West German marks, down from 1.8665; 1.5593 Swiss francs, down from 1.5725; 6.2985 French francs, down from 6.3365; 2.0933 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1050; 1,378.60 Italian lire, down from 1,388.50; and 1.2335 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2362 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound rose to $ 1.6850, compared with $ 1.6755 Friday. Gold was weakened by private investors, particularly from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, selling bullion, dealers in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said. `` It's a familiar pattern,'' said one. `` With the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> out, a few players try to push a thin market.'' Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 428.10 a troy ounce, up from $ 427.50 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 427. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 426.90, down from $ 428 bid late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell 1.54 to close at a bid 429.38. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 6.48 a troy ounce, down from Friday's $ 6.52.
