<HEAD>Hotel Magnate Fighting Conglomerate For Hotel</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was a cold November day in 1966 when attorney and expectant-father <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> looked out a downtown hospital window toward the vacant grounds of his alma mater, <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION>. The international exposition <PERSON> HemisFair </PERSON> was two years away and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> knew the city needed hotel rooms in the tourist area. So as his daughter was being delivered, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> devised a plan to turn the Colonial Spanish-style campus into a luxury hotel with a view of the popular River Walk. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s gamble in what became La Mansion del Rio paid off. Tourists crowded into the hotel when it opened in April 1968 and have been coming ever since. Today, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> is fighting for survival and claiming that one of his lenders, <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, backed him into a financial corner to steal his hotels for its own hotel management subsidiary. It's a lawsuit the hotel industry is watching carefully. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s attorneys say his $ 7 billion lawsuit against Metropolitan could be a test case because it charges that a lender, in calculated moves, conspired to become a direct competitor with its borrower. `` My biggest problem with this case is trying to understand why a company with over $ 100 billion worth of assets and 100 years of reputable business dealings would stoop to this practice, and that is the reason I am willing to go through with this lawsuit,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said recently. Metropolitan officials deny any wrongdoing and say the case is a simple contractual agreement that <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> broke by not paying his bills on time. `` I think you are seeing an absolute desperation move,'' said Metropolitan's <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> attorney, <PERSON> Seagal </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheatley </PERSON>. `` What you have is a straight-forward loan. Met breached no agreement with Mr. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Wheatley </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> is using the lawsuit to avoid a threatened bankruptcy. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s lawsuit charges Metropolitan with fraud, duress, interference, deceptive trade practices, breach of confidential relationships, unfair dealing and conspiracy in what he claims was a concerted nationwide effort by <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> and its Phoenix-based subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> Doubletree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, to take over regional, profitable hotels at a fraction of their worth. The fight is scheduled for another round in court on Sept. 12, but Metropolitan already claims partial victory from state District Judge <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Curry </PERSON>'s summary judgment in August that Metropolitan and <ORGANIZATION> Doubletree </ORGANIZATION> did not conspire to take over La Mansion. But <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s attorneys are pressing ahead, claiming that Metropolitan wants to postpone a jury trial until 1989 to drain <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s resources. `` If we can get to a jury and show a jury how Metropolitan was telling <ORGANIZATION> Doubletree </ORGANIZATION> that they would be taking over La Mansion hotels, even before <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> had any problems, and then put the incredible squeeze on <PERSON> Pat </PERSON>, I think a jury is going to be offended,'' said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Macon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was 36 when he transformed the old campus into a luxury hotel. Success fueled expansion desires and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> approached Metropolitan. In July 1978, the 300-room La Mansion del Norte opened in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> with an $ 8.1 million loan from the insurer. In 1981, Metropolitan refinanced <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s mortgage to expand the chain again, increasing his loan to $ 11.25 million. In 1982, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, in partnership with an investment group, started construction of <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mansion-Austin </ORGANIZATION> financed by Metropolitan servicing agent <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The 300-room <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> hotel opened in April 1984. The three hotels, <LOCATION> Macon </LOCATION> claims, are worth about $ 80 million. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> alleges that between 1981 and 1984, Metropolitan began thinking of taking over La Mansion after the insurance giant acquired 20 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Doubletree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotels </ORGANIZATION>. With the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> economy on a slide in the mid-1980s, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s hotels suffered like others During that time, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> alleges, Metropolitan told <ORGANIZATION> Doubletree </ORGANIZATION> his hotels were in trouble and could become targets for <ORGANIZATION> Doubletree </ORGANIZATION> takeovers. In July 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Doubletree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotels </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> contacted him about a franchising plan, but <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> declined the offer, he said. That fall <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> decided to restructure his management company and began talking to his lenders. He claims he could not reach a satisfactory arrangement with Metropolitan. `` We reduced his monthly payments by 50 percent and he claims that we dealt very hard with him,'' said <PERSON> Wheatley </PERSON>. The attorney said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s 1986 restructuring earned him more than $ 1 million at a time <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> claimed he could n't make payments for his north property. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> talked with other lenders and agreed to give up ownership but retain management control of La Mansion del Rio and <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Mansion-Austin </PERSON>. In the summer of 1987, unable to find an investor in the hotel, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> received an extension on his loan payment from Metropolitan, but by that December, <PERSON> Arnholt </PERSON> declared the loan in default and threatened foreclosure on La Mansion del Norte. The same month, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> posted <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Mansion-Austin </PERSON> for foreclosure and fired <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s management company. This January, <ORGANIZATION> Doubletree </ORGANIZATION> began to manage the <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> hotel after <PERSON> Wheatley </PERSON> claimed it exhausted its search for a management company. In February, Metropolitan planned to foreclose on La Mansion del Norte and <ORGANIZATION> Doubletree </ORGANIZATION> employees prepared to move in, but <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> filed suit, obtained a temporary restraining order and kept Metropolitan from taking over. Now, Metropolitan claims that <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> is on a free ride, not having paid a dime for the hotel's debt service since 1986 while continuing to draw fees for managing the hotel. Attorneys for both sides said they're not sure what will happen on Sept. 12.
