<SECOND>AM-Business Ethics, Bjt,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harvard Business School Adds Required Ethics Class</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Case: <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> wants to replace two assembly plants but keep operations near <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. The only available site is in <LOCATION> Poletown </LOCATION> _ and if the company builds there it has to level 1,200 homes and force out 3,500 residents. Case: <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> must decide whether to support a federal toxic substances control act after one of its pesticides encounters environmental problems. It also must grapple with an internal policy that would restrict some product uses _ and sales. What should a corporate executive do? Spurred in part by complex new moral dilemmas and publicized incidents of criminal wrongdoing, the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> is requiring its 800 incoming students this fall to think about those and other ethical questions. Scholars said the three-week mini-course at the 80-year-old graduate school is part of a nationwide trend to devote more resources to teaching and research on moral reasoning and ethical values in corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` It's become sufficiently clear that the business leader of the future is going to have to be conversant and thoughtful about ethics,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodpaster </PERSON>, a philosopher who came to the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in 1980 to help develop an ethics curriculum. One goal of the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> course is to make future business leaders consider the impact of their decisions. It joins philosophy with case study to stimulate dialogue on questions that defy easy answers. The <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> course will tackle such topics as corporate responsibility in a plant relocation, limits of economic reasoning in environmental waste issues, conflicting cultural values in international business, and organizational pressures against honesty and integrity. What courses at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and other universities do n't do is prescribe a set of morals. You ca n't teach ethics, scholars said; graduate students bring with them values developed over a lifetime. `` We're not trying to make bad people all of a sudden turn into saints,'' said <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciulla </PERSON>, a philosopher who teaches ethics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's not coming up with the right answer. It's going through the process and understanding what are the issues and what are the values _ what do we have to think about here?'' Business ethics is n't a new field. In 1915, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> offered a class on `` Social Factors in Business Enterprise.'' After the 1929 stock market crash, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> hired a philosopher to teach ethics as society reacted to the Depression by attacking greed in business. <PERSON> Wharton </PERSON>, which has three ethics specialists, this year for the first time is requiring students to attend two ethics sessions during orientation. International business students take a class on cross-cultural ethics, while the graduate and undergraduate divisions have offered a business ethics course since 1975. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s business school has required a course on social responsibility since the the mid-1960s, the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> has had an applied ethics center for about 20 years and requires first-year students to take a class similar to <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s, while <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> offers an ethics elective. With an increasing number of cases like the <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> insider trading and the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> defense scandals, those schools are intensifying research in ethics, and <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> is hosting a conference on the subject in December. Still, only about 10 percent of business students nationwide are required to study ethics. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> last year received a reported $ 20 million pledge from former <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Shad </PERSON> to study ethics, part of a university-wide program to boost research in the field in the professional schools. Scholars said the study of business over the last 30 years has become more scientific _ numbers-crunching and bottom-line analysis at the expense of ethics, corporate purpose and corporate responsibility. `` I do n't have difficulty putting forth certain values where at least alarms ought to go off,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Piper </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s senior associate dean for education programs `` But I also think the emphasis should be on the awareness of the breadth of impact.'' Starting in the late 1950s and'60s, business schools emphasized that the goal of a company should be maximizing the individual stockholder's wealth. Now researchers talk about the impact of business decisions on all `` stakeholders'' _ workers, communities, customers, future generations. `` Wherever you draw the line on insider trading, meeting someone in an alley with $ 400,000 in a suitcase is not a hard issue,'' said <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Olsson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> of Applied Ethics. `` The more important stuff is how do you put ethics in the center of business decision-making every day,'' he said. `` We try to make students understand that in every decision they make, they're making a moral choice.''
</TEXT>
