<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices closed higher Monday, helped by lingering bullish sentiment from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employment figures released last Friday. Price markups by market participants extended a rally begun Friday on the back of the unemployment data, which showed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy did not expand in August quite as fast as had been expected. The data allayed concerns that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates still might have to rise further to douse an overheating economy. Analysts said shares were also moving better because, for the time being, fears of rising <LOCATION> U.K. </LOCATION> interest rates have been pushed into the background. However, market watchers were quick to point out that participation remained painfully low Monday. At the end of trading, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index was up 17.6 points, or 1.00 percent, at 1764.5. The index opened 10.2 points higher and bounced as much as 20.4 points higher by mid-morning to its best level of the day. Meanwhile, the narrower <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 30-share index was up 14.6 points at 1420.5. Volume was extremely light, with a scant 284.8 million shares changing hands, compared with the 443.8 million shares Friday. Of Monday's total, 192.2 million shares had been traded by midday. Market activity was light in response to a lack of leadership from Wall Street, which was closed Monday for the Labor Day holiday. However, several analysts stressed the market's firm undertone after Friday's healthy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employment figures for August and a 52-point bounce upwards on the Dow Jones Industrial Average. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> August unemployment rate rose to 5.6 percent and non-farm payroll jobs created totaled 219,000. The revised July unemployment rate remained unchanged at 5.4 percent but the non-farm payroll gain was revised downward to 200,000 jobs from 283,000 jobs. Market expectations had been for a 5.4-percent unemployment rate and non-farm payrolls at 224,000.
