<TEXT>
 The chief negotiator for the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> opened talks Monday with government officials on <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s request for a stand-by loan of about $ 1.2 billion. <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Lachman </PERSON> was scheduled to meet with <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> officials to discuss, among other topics, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s balance of payments and the anti-inflation plan implemented by President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> early last month. The <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> funds would be used in part to help <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> pay interest on its $ 56 billion foreign debt. Interest payments on the debt will total about $ 4.6 billion this year alone. Last week, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> reportedly won preliminary approval from the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> for two loans totaling $ 750 million to reform its banking system and reorient its trade policy, including the lifting of restrictions on imports. <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Machinea </PERSON> said early last week he expected an agreement would be concluded by week's end. However, no official statement was issued before the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shamid </PERSON> <PERSON> Husain </PERSON>, returned to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lachman </PERSON> is scheduled to be in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> for about a week. Since <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> took office in December 1983, government policy has been to finance 