<SECOND>BC-WPPSS-Settlement,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engineering Firm Settles Two Days Before Federal Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An engineering firm that acted as a consultant to the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Public Supply System on abortive plans to build two nuclear power plants has settled with bondholders for $ 20 million, officials said Monday. The settlement between R.W. <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> and Associates of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and bondholders was announced in a statement released by court-appointed settlement master <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>. It came two days before the scheduled start of a massive securities fraud case against <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> in federal court here. The agreement is subject to approval by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, who will preside over the case in which 21 public utilities, two engineering firms and a financial adviser remain as defendants. More than 24,000 bondholders and <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, the trustee for bondholders, allege that the supply system fraudulently sold $ 2.25 billion in bonds to build the plants. The project was abandoned in 1982 and the supply system declared default in 1983 after the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled the public utilities involved in the project had no authorization to sign agreements with <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>. Monday's announcement brought the total settlements so far to $ 351 million. Agreement has been reached on an additional $ 96 million in claims against insurance companies, although the bondholders must pursue lawsuits to obtain any of that money. Last Wednesday the supply system itself settled with the bondholders for an estimated $ 3 billion, the cost of the bonds plus interest. Bondholders were expected to see little of that settlement money, however, because the supply system has few assets to use to pay back the bonds.
