<FIRST>u f AM-WPPSSTrial 2ndLd-Writethru   09-05 1079</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WPPSS Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru,1110</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Five Years, WPPSS Fraud Case Goes To Trial In Tucson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf to update with $351 million in settlements so
far, sted $331 million; picks up 17th graf pvs, ``WPPSS itself
...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>^LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five years and more than $ 150 million in legal fees later, a giant fraud case stemming from the biggest default in the history of the municipal bond market is headed for trial Wednesday in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>. The litigation in federal court is a consolidation of dozens of lawsuits filed by bondholders after the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>'s 1983 default on $ 2.25 billion in bonds sold to finance construction of two nuclear power plants. Though it has remained obscure, the so-called `` Whoops'' case has won notoriety in legal and financial circles for its size and complexity. Consider: _ Since about 1980 market defaults have totaled about $ 5.7 billion `` Forty percent of that is <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehmann </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, treasurer of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> 4-5 Bondholders Committee. _ Dozens of attorneys from some 70 law firms, with rates as high as $ 400 an hour, have been involved in pre-trial work Still to be added to the legal tab are trial costs and the fees of many attorneys who have worked for five years on contingency. _ A computerized data-retrieval system for the plaintiffs' side alone has cost more than $ 35 million, and it holds 14 million documents and hundreds of statements by witnesses The defense is keeping its system secret. _ More than 24,000 claims have been filed by an estimated 42,000 bondholders _ Defendants, from Wall Street bond underwriting firms to 88 public utilities to law firms and economic advisers, originally numbered more than 100 Some, including bond underwriters, have settled outside court for $ 331 million so far. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> itself was let out of the suit last week in a surprise move, leaving 21 utilities and engineering and financial adviser firms as defendants. _ The trial itself could last up to two years `` The WPPSS case is unique,'' said <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> Professor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamb </PERSON>, who has written a book on the supply system's woes. `` There is nothing like it. Not only in the dollar amount, but in the complexity of the involvements of different layers of government and governmental authority, the complexity of the number of litigants, claimants, and participants.'' `` All the major brokerage firms were involved, the -LRB- bond -RRB- rating agencies were involved, bond counsel were involved, and different engineering firms, accounting firms, as well as all layers of government,'' he said. Those complexities aside, however, and the case comes down to who will pick up the tab for the WPPSS default and the ensuing legal battle _ bondholders alleging fraud who are stuck with nearly worthless bonds, or electric utility customers in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> who will have to pay higher rates if a decision goes against them. `` The public is suing the public,'' <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON>, commissioner of <LOCATION> Snohomish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Public </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Utility </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, a defendant, said in describing the large groups of potential losers. Despite the risk of losing, with the potential of a multibillion-dollar judgment, settlement efforts have fallen short as trial looms. The $ 351 million in settlements so far include $ 92 million from bond underwriters and most of the rest from insurance. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> itself was a relatively minor defendant in the recovery because others named in the action have more resources to tap. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, as part of its settlement, agreed not to contest the future payment of money to reimburse claimants. Left among defendants are only 20 <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> utilities, an <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> utility, two engineering firms and a financial advisory firm. But those 21 utilities held about a two-thirds interest in the abandoned plants. While settlement was encouraged by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, efforts to reach a `` global settlement'' involving all parties fell short last May when defendants declined to counter a plaintiff offer of something in excess of $ 1 billion. Without such a settlement, the case could last for years, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratcliffe </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, who retired a year ago as deputy administrator of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's a lose-lose proposition every day that litigation goes on,'' he said. `` If the litigation runs its course, it wo n't be resolved until well into the next century.'' For the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, he said, the fighting will continue to have economic costs and take a toll in ill-will and lack of cooperation by various energy and governmental entities. For the bondholders: `` I do n't think any of those living today will see any money. Maybe their heirs will,'' <PERSON> Ratcliffe </PERSON> said. And for attorneys? `` I wish I was still practicing law ... since this is such a marvelous opportunity,'' <PERSON> Ratcliffe </PERSON>, a lawyer, said sardonically. To bondholders, the case is one of giant fraud and conspiracy, coupled with a shameless lack of integrity among defendants, including the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> as a region. They say utilities knowingly entered into faulty agreements with the supply system to build the two plants, <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> Nos. 4 and 5. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in June 1983 that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> utilities among the 88 participants contracting to build the plants lacked authority to sign the pacts and did not have to pay. <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, trustee for bondholders, accelerated debt payment that August, precipitating the default on the debt. Ratepayer representatives say misguided leadership in the 1970s, faulty projections for energy needs, poor planning and reliance on experts who were simply wrong were among factors that led the region astray. Utility commissioners wrongly believed the plants would be needed to prevent power brown-outs and the public would accept big rate hikes, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lazar </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>, a utility consultant. `` They are not on trial for being stupid,'' he said. `` They are on trial for fraud, and that is different.'' Others said the mishap at the <LOCATION> Three </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> nuclear plant in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and a worldwide economic downturn were both critical. Though ratepayers have so far escaped paying for WPPSS Nos. 4 and 5, electric rates have increased five-fold in the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> to pay for three other <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> nuclear plants. The rates are assessed through <LOCATION> Bonneville </LOCATION>, a federal power marketing agency, which in effect guaranteed payments for the three plants. That BPA payment-guarantee was not forthcoming for the terminated plants. Trial was moved to <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> on a motion that a jury of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> residents might be reluctant to return a decision that could raise their electricity rates.
