<HEAD>Venezuelan bank plans to open gold-buying office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, faced with falling oil export revenue, announced Monday one of its banks will open an office in the gold-mining region of the country to buy gold directly from miners. Finalven plans to open an office in <LOCATION> Guayana </LOCATION>, some 400 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Venpress </ORGANIZATION> announced. The new office would buy gold directly from miners at world market rates, said Finalven President <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Minister. Currently <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> is pushing to expand its gold production in the wake of falling oil export revenue. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> is supposed to produce 20 thousand pounds of gold this year, up from 11 thousand in 1987, according to official estimates. Experts estimate that much of the mined gold is smuggled out of the country in search of better rates. Until recently, there was no centralized system of aquiring the precious metal from the miners, who work independently in the primitive region near the Brazilian border. The Venezuelan <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> opened an office earlier this year that also purchases gold directly from the miners.
